  "text": "Scenario I was identified in tests TBoom 12 and TBoom 14, starting at OC states, whereas Scenario II was recognised as developing during monotonic heating tests TBoom 2 and TPon 2 on the remoulded Pontida clay [CITATION_1] . The hallmark of Scenario II is a compressive axial strain rate in the presence of an increasing pore pressure. This is distinguished from Scenario I, where a compressive axial strain rate develops from an initial expansive strain at a later stage of heating (at higher temperatures), but is accompanied by a decreasing pore pressure, as seen in TBoom 14. In test TBoom 14, the pore [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] pressure started decreasing from its maximum value of 1 . 1 MPa at about 798C, despite further heating up to 848C. The drop in pore pressure is not very large (0 . 11 MPa), but it is persistent. For further experimental data and discussion of undrained deviatoric thermal failure, including during cyclic heating and cooling, see and Del [CITATION_4] .",
